{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504755"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:20:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:20:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2364"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2364"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.33,0.15,0.43,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2364"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51189"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2364"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2364"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36461"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"348"},{"type":"tags","id":"1251"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"4891"},{"type":"tags","id":"6563"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11855"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14627"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51189"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn ambulance is called for a 73-year-old woman unable to mobilise due to weakness of the right arm and leg. By the time she arrives at the Emergency Department, the symptoms have however resolved. On further history, the patient has previously had a similar, but less severe, episode of transient right-sided weakness. There have also been two instances of episodes of loss of vision in the left eye, which lasted minutes. Her medical history includes hypertension and dyslipidaemia. She has a 20 pack-year smoking history and drinks one to two standard drinks each night.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the patient appears well with a blood pressure of 125/75 mmHg and pulse  95/min. Neurological examination is normal. A CT scan is performed, which excludes intracranial haemorrhage. There are no features of early ischaemia and no masses are identified.\u00a0Carotid ultrasound reveals an 80% stenosis of the left internal carotid artery (ICA) and complete occlusion of the right ICA. This is confirmed via CT angiogram.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin monotherapy, with atorvastatin and amlodipine","Left carotid endarterectomy","Right carotid endarterectomy","Bilateral carotid endarterectomy","Transfer to an acute stroke centre for consideration of cerebral angiogram"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient likely experienced a transient ischaemic attack (TIA) consistent with left internal carotid artery (ICA) stenosis, with ipsilateral amaurosis fugax and contralateral weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft carotid endarterectomy \u003C/strong\u003Eis indicated given there is high-grade stenosis. There is a clear benefit to endarterectomy in carotid artery stenosis of 70-99% with a history of TIA or stroke, the evidence is strongest if performed within two weeks. Given the known right carotid artery occlusions the left CEA will be performed by placing a vascular shunt during the procedure. It is placed into the lumens of the common carotid artery and the ICA essentially bypassing the area requiring the endarterectomy whilst maintaining antegrade flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarotid endarterectomy (CEA) is not suitable if there is complete occlusion, as there are no branches of the internal carotid artery from origin to carotid syphon, the artery is chronically thrombosed all the way to the brain and cannot be re-opened. As such, neither \u003Cstrong\u003Eright \u003C/strong\u003Enor \u003Cstrong\u003Ebilateral carotid endarterectomy \u003C/strong\u003Eis indicated. There is no indication for CEA in complete internal carotid artery occlusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to surgery, this patient will be started on dual anti-platelet therapy (DAPT). Based on current evidence, \u003Cstrong\u003Easpirin monotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is inferior to DAPT in the acute setting. For secondary prevention of cardiovascular disease, the patient requires an ACE inhibitor, statin (such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eatorvastatin\u003C/strong\u003E) and indefinite aspirin following cessation of DAPT. At this stage there is no acute indication for \u003Cstrong\u003Eamlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E. Of note: without MRI a stroke cannot be definitively excluded at this stage and permissive hypertension in the acute setting may be warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA cerebral angiogram \u003C/strong\u003Eis not indicated in the treatment or investigation of TIA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["There is no indication for carotid endarterectomy in complete carotid stenosis."],"references":["Cardiovascular disease risk stratification. In: eTG Complete [Internet]. 2017. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Johnston S, Easton J, Farrant M, Barsan W, Conwit R, Elm J et al. Clopidogrel and Aspirin in Acute Ischemic Stroke and High-Risk TIA. N Eng J Med. 2018;379(3):215-225. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6193486/","Stroke and transient ischaemic attack  In: eTG Complete [Internet]. 2017. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Wang Y, Wang Y, Zhao X. Clopidogrel with Aspirin in Acute Minor Stroke or Transient Ischemic Attack. J Vasc Surg. 2013;58(4):1140. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMoa1215340?url_ver=Z39.88-2003\u0026rfr_id=ori:rid:crossref.org\u0026rfr_dat=cr_pub%20%200www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36461"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2364"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36461"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-21T23:45:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-21T23:46:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2364"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51189"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},